04147nam a22006615i 9780271034874DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710348747 a10.1515/97802710348742doi  a(DE-B1597)583951  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0340002bisacsh04a327.1/722221 aHartzell, Caroline A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCrafting Peace :bPower-Sharing Institutions and the Negotiated Settlement of Civil Wars /cCaroline A. Hartzell, Matthew Hoddie. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of abbreviations and acronyms -- tIntroduction: Institutions and the Negotiated Settlement of Civil Wars -- t1 After the Fighting Stops: Security Concerns, Institutions, and the Post-Civil War Environment -- t2 Creating Power-Sharing and Power-Dividing Institutions -- t3 Institutionalizing an Enduring Peace -- t4 Implementing Power-Sharing and Power-Dividing Agreements -- t5 Negotiating for Peace in Angola and the Philippines: Case Studies of Failure and Success -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe recent efforts to reach a settlement of the enduring and tragic conflict in Darfur demonstrate how important it is to understand what factors contribute most to the success of such efforts. In this book, Caroline Hartzell and Matthew Hoddie review data from all negotiated civil war settlements between 1945 and 1999 in order to identify these factors.What they find is that settlements are more likely to produce an enduring peace if they involve construction of a diversity of power-sharing and power-dividing arrangements between former adversaries. The strongest negotiated settlements prove to be those in which former rivals agree to share or divide state power across its economic, military, political, and territorial dimensions.This finding is a significant addition to the existing literature, which tends to focus more on the role that third parties play in mediating and enforcing agreements. Beyond the quantitative analyses, the authors include a chapter comparing contrasting cases of successful and unsuccessful settlements in the Philippines and Angola, respectively.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCivil war. 0aPacific settlement of international disputes. 0aPeace-building. 0aPower (Social sciences). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh1 aHoddie, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271034874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271034874.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK